Indian Embassy Attestation Process 
Step by Step Embassy Attestation Process for Indian Issued Documents in UAE
Step 1: Document Verification

Check that your document is original and issued by a recognized authority in India.
Ensure all details are correct and legible.
Step 2: Attestation in India (If Required)

Certain documents need state-level approval.
Ministry of External Affairs (MEA) attestation may also be needed.
This confirms your document is genuine before embassy submission.
Step 3: Indian Embassy or Consulate Attestation in UAE

Submit your document to the Indian Embassy in Abu Dhabi or Consulate in Dubai.
Embassy staff verify the authenticity and place an official stamp.
Step 4: UAE MOFA Attestation

The Ministry of Foreign Affairs in UAE provides final approval.
This makes your document legally valid for use with UAE authorities.
Step 5: Secure Document Delivery

After all approvals, your attested document is returned safely.
Now it can be used for visas, legal, property, employment, or business purposes.
Indian Embassy Marriage Certificate Attestation Process
Marriage certificate attestation is usually needed when you want to use your marriage certificate for family visa, spouse sponsorship, or immigration in the UAE. The process confirms that your certificate is genuine and legally valid.

Step 1: Marriage certificate verification

We check that the original marriage certificate is correct and complete.
Confirm that it is issued by the proper Indian authority.
Make sure the language is readable and clear.
Step 2: Attestation in India

Some marriage certificates need approval from the State or Home Department in India.
Then it is verified by the Ministry of External Affairs (MEA).
This step confirms the certificate is authentic before sending it to the UAE.
Step 3: Indian Embassy or Consulate attestation in UAE

Submit your certificate to the Indian Embassy in Abu Dhabi or the Consulate in Dubai.
The embassy staff checks your certificate and places an official stamp.
This shows the document is genuine for international use.
Step 4: UAE MOFA attestation

The Ministry of Foreign Affairs in the UAE gives the final approval.
This step makes your marriage certificate legally accepted by UAE authorities.
After these steps, your marriage certificate is ready to use for visas, immigration, or any official requirement in the UAE.

Indian Embassy Power of Attorney Attestation Process
A Power of Attorney (POA) is a legal document granting another person the authority to act for you. It must be handled carefully to be valid in the UAE.

Step 1: Draft review

Check that the purpose of the POA is clear.
Make sure the wording is correct so it works legally.
Step 2: Signing and notarisation

The document must be signed properly.
Identity of the signer is verified to avoid problems later.
Step 3: Attestation in India

Some POAs need approval from local authorities in India.
The Ministry of External Affairs (MEA) also verifies the document.
Step 4: Submit for Indian Embassy/Consulate Verification in UAE

For attestation, the POA must be submitted to the Indian Embassy in Abu Dhabi or the Consulate in Dubai, where officials will confirm its authenticity
The embassy checks and stamps the document to confirm authenticity.
Step 5: UAE MOFA attestation

The Ministry of Foreign Affairs in UAE provides final approval.
Once done, the POA is legally valid for property, banking, or business use in the UAE.
